23:22.195 --> 23:23.656
Lobster was seen as a pest.

23:23.696 --> 23:25.398
The only people
who used them regularly

23:25.428 --> 23:27.029
was the prison system.

23:27.059 --> 23:29.200
The prisoners rioted because
they said this is cruel

23:29.230 --> 23:31.361
and unusual punishment having
to eat lobster every day.

23:31.402 --> 23:33.203
"No, I don't want that.
It's lobster."

23:43.910 --> 23:46.942
Nobody knows who first
salt-baked a fish.

23:46.972 --> 23:48.343
Maybe it was Jesus.

23:48.373 --> 23:50.514
- Ohhh.
- Oh, wow.

23:50.544 --> 23:53.546
Scale and gut your fish,
in this case a sea bass,

23:53.576 --> 23:55.418
insert lemon and onion,

23:55.448 --> 23:57.319
then pack it in salt and bake.

24:01.982 --> 24:04.253
Light the whole thing
on fire tableside,

24:04.283 --> 24:05.854
then break open.

24:05.884 --> 24:07.886
The salt acts like
a protective crust,

24:07.926 --> 24:10.458
sealing in all
the moisture and flavor.

24:10.488 --> 24:13.930
Now, that looks beautiful.
That's perfect food.

24:13.960 --> 24:15.631
Mmm.

24:15.661 --> 24:17.632
Clams cooked Portuguese style.

24:17.662 --> 24:19.734
- Yeah.
- So tender and sweet

24:19.764 --> 24:21.635
and delicious.

24:21.665 --> 24:23.266
Why do you think Portuguese food

24:23.296 --> 24:25.438
has not had a higher profile
internationally?

24:25.468 --> 24:30.241
Well, for me it's
real easy to say this,

24:30.271 --> 24:31.942
it's basically...
It's your fault.

24:31.972 --> 24:33.903
- Our fault?
- It's the Americans' fault.

24:33.943 --> 24:35.274
Yeah.
Why?

24:35.304 --> 24:37.305
The American culture
embraced Spain.

24:37.345 --> 24:39.807
It embraced Italy.
It embraced France.

24:39.847 --> 24:43.109
It didn't embrace Portugal
because... I don't know.

24:43.149 --> 24:45.081
If we have a civil war

24:45.111 --> 24:47.482
so popular like the Spanish had,

24:47.512 --> 24:49.584
and Hemmingway came
to Portugal instead of Spain,

24:49.614 --> 24:51.985
we would be a different country.

24:52.015 --> 24:54.117
You know, you think of Italy,
you think of romance.

24:54.157 --> 24:56.488
- No, but we are romantic.
- I know. These people...

24:56.518 --> 24:58.327
We are the most romantic
country in the world.

24:58.359 --> 25:00.061
After you have a couple
of meals in Porto,

25:00.091 --> 25:03.493
you're going to feel saudade
in your heart and soul.

25:03.523 --> 25:07.466
Man, good meal.
Oh, what, there's more clams?

25:07.496 --> 25:10.167
Right over here, my friend.

25:48.723 --> 25:51.255
Contrary to what some might say,

25:51.295 --> 25:55.528
I do not enjoy seeing
the death of any living thing.

25:55.558 --> 25:58.159
I do not promote animal cruelty.

26:18.573 --> 26:20.514
- Yeah, ready to go?
- Yep.

26:20.544 --> 26:23.876
Kill the pig, kill the pig,
kill the pig.

26:23.916 --> 26:27.479
But I think people should
know where meat comes from,

26:27.519 --> 26:30.051
and knowing, they should
feel free to decide

26:30.081 --> 26:32.382
what they want to do from there.

26:38.256 --> 26:40.758
- It's the least you could do.
- Yeah, exactly, so...

26:42.229 --> 26:45.891
Here, right here
on Jose's family farm,

26:45.931 --> 26:48.533
is where I saw
my first animal die.

26:48.563 --> 26:50.234
A pig too.

26:50.264 --> 26:52.295
This, after years and decades

26:52.335 --> 26:54.067
of being a chef, serving meat,

26:54.097 --> 26:55.798
ordering up my death
over the phone

26:55.838 --> 26:57.839
at a comfortable distance.

26:57.869 --> 27:00.671
Up close, it was not
so comfortable.

27:00.701 --> 27:02.672
I think he's starting
to get the bad news.

27:02.702 --> 27:05.004
I guess on the DNA, they know
that's gonna happen and...

27:05.044 --> 27:06.845
They know it's coming.

27:06.875 --> 27:08.869
- Really they know it's coming.
- Yeah, well the pigs are smart.

27:08.876 --> 27:11.979
And sometimes
they manage to run away.

27:12.009 --> 27:15.551
To do the job right,
professionals are brought in,

27:15.581 --> 27:17.182
and they do it
like this because,

27:17.212 --> 27:19.654
how shall I put it,
they need the heart

27:19.684 --> 27:22.185
to keep pumping the blood
into the pail

27:22.215 --> 27:24.057
for sausage and soup,

27:24.087 --> 27:26.088
and many delicious things.

27:37.125 --> 27:41.068
We all come to this in the end,

27:41.098 --> 27:43.399
whether struggling for air
in our beds,

27:43.430 --> 27:45.601
bleeding out on cold concrete,

27:45.631 --> 27:49.033
a last mighty dump like Elvis,

27:49.073 --> 27:50.534
or this.

28:03.643 --> 28:06.245
Oh, yeah, it's a firecracker.

28:08.246 --> 28:10.688
That's the start of
any festivities in Portugal,

28:10.718 --> 28:13.289
is the firecracker.
Really?

28:13.319 --> 28:16.692
As befitting tradition
and the way things are done,

28:16.722 --> 28:18.893
this is a once in a year event.

28:18.923 --> 28:21.025
For two days, extended family,

28:21.055 --> 28:23.126
friends and neighbors
gather to cook,

28:23.156 --> 28:25.027
cure and eat a pig.

28:25.057 --> 28:27.259
Time for a haircut?
Yeah, haircut.

28:27.299 --> 28:29.030
- Old-school.
- Yeah.

28:34.664 --> 28:36.705
They finish up
with the blowtorch.

28:36.735 --> 28:39.467
- As one must.
- Yeah.

28:55.147 --> 28:56.548
It's like rappers.

28:56.578 --> 28:58.249
Yeah, yeah,
that's it, that's it.

28:58.279 --> 29:00.021
Free style.

29:27.299 --> 29:28.640
Up.

29:28.670 --> 29:32.242
Up. There you go.

29:34.804 --> 29:37.606
So now they gonna finish up
and take all the guts out...

29:37.646 --> 29:40.007
Take all the guts out,
and that is lunch.

29:40.047 --> 29:41.678
Lunch time.

29:41.708 --> 29:43.409
In Portugal, we used to say

29:43.450 --> 29:45.311
that if we want
to know our body,

29:45.351 --> 29:48.253
you have to kill a pig because
it's absolutely the same.

29:48.283 --> 29:51.985
All the organs are placed
on the same disposition.

29:52.015 --> 29:54.817
I see a liver there
and the heart,

29:54.857 --> 29:56.658
and you have
the tongue there too.

29:56.688 --> 29:59.360
That's all in a package,
all the good stuff.

30:00.721 --> 30:02.963
Look, it's a lung.

30:05.894 --> 30:07.125
He's good.

30:07.165 --> 30:09.027
Yeah, he really knows
what he's doing.

30:09.067 --> 30:11.868
I would say a surgeon,
but he's faster than a surgeon.

30:19.734 --> 30:22.806
Guts removed, the liver
and heart are used today.

30:22.836 --> 30:24.377
Cooked immediately.

30:24.407 --> 30:26.338
Oh, this is the best, the heart.

30:26.378 --> 30:29.380
- It's like a tender sirloin.
- Oh, it's so good.

30:29.410 --> 30:30.681
It's so good, yeah.

30:30.711 --> 30:32.212
The intestines washed

30:32.242 --> 30:34.844
and reserved for sausage casing.

30:37.315 --> 30:38.786
Mmm. Looks nice.

30:38.816 --> 30:41.388
The rest is left to hang
until tomorrow,

30:41.418 --> 30:43.990
when we shall feast again.

30:48.193 --> 30:51.655
- Ah, it's like chicharron.
- Chicharron.

30:53.026 --> 30:54.527
Oh, wow.

30:55.558 --> 30:56.858
Yeah, yeah.

30:56.898 --> 30:59.930
Oh.
That's kind of perfect.

31:03.333 --> 31:05.204
Mmm.
That's good.

31:05.234 --> 31:08.006
Not all of the countries
eat all of the meat

31:08.036 --> 31:09.237
off of the pork.

31:09.267 --> 31:11.768
And here, we eat everything.

31:18.273 --> 31:20.674
- They don't waste anything.
- Anything.

32:15.981 --> 32:20.184
Fado, the national music
of Portugal.

32:20.214 --> 32:22.886
Songs of longing, heartbreak,

32:22.916 --> 32:25.117
saudade set to music.

32:46.972 --> 32:48.773
Anthony, in Portugal

32:48.803 --> 32:51.875
everybody thinks
that they sing Fado.

32:51.905 --> 32:54.637
We, the Portuguese,
think that the Fado

32:54.677 --> 32:56.938
is not the perfection,

32:56.979 --> 33:00.241
the ability, the fine-tuning.

33:00.281 --> 33:05.314
It's emotion, so everybody's
allowed to sing.

33:05.344 --> 33:06.885
Yeah.

33:06.915 --> 33:09.547
That's why Jose is
telling that I sing Fado.

33:09.587 --> 33:11.218
I see.

33:11.248 --> 33:15.051
Normally the guys who sing
Fado are very happy guys.

33:15.091 --> 33:18.323
They are very...
But when they begin to sing,

33:18.353 --> 33:20.154
they turn into sad guys.

33:20.194 --> 33:21.725
I don't know why.

33:21.755 --> 33:24.957
Well, you said
the Portuguese are bipolar.

33:24.997 --> 33:27.229
Yes, yes they are.
They are.

33:28.930 --> 33:32.502
So ready to eat, I see, huh?
Big enough table?

33:37.866 --> 33:40.267
The home of Jose's
ancestors for centuries.

33:40.307 --> 33:44.840
Much of their original estate
still in family hands.

33:53.846 --> 33:55.447
Very exciting.

33:55.477 --> 33:57.619
Jose's mother Maria
is in charge today.

33:57.649 --> 34:01.051
She's preparing a feast of
rustic Portuguese soul food.

34:11.058 --> 34:13.129
They boil the bones out,

34:13.159 --> 34:15.184
then they finish with the
blood, so... blood and bread.

34:15.190 --> 34:17.993
- Blood and bread.
- Yeah.

34:18.033 --> 34:20.333
Mmm.

34:20.364 --> 34:22.435
Beautiful.

34:26.398 --> 34:28.739
It's so good.

34:36.645 --> 34:40.708
The main event, cozido,

34:40.748 --> 34:44.480
a glorious stew of seemingly
every last part of the pig.

34:44.510 --> 34:46.712
I'm gonna give you
some of the pernil,

34:46.752 --> 34:49.152
that is the smoked meat.

34:49.183 --> 34:50.714
Spare ribs.

34:50.754 --> 34:52.686
Nothing goes to waste
around here.

34:52.716 --> 34:54.717
The blood sausage.
Cabbage.

34:54.757 --> 34:56.888
- Oh, what's that?
- That's the butelo.

34:56.918 --> 35:00.191
It's the pig's bladder
that's stuffed with pork belly,

35:00.221 --> 35:02.462
the spare ribs, and then smoked.

35:02.492 --> 35:04.323
Wow, look at that.

35:06.325 --> 35:08.126
Extraordinary.

35:13.399 --> 35:15.531
And one little thing,
you don't feel that guilty

35:15.571 --> 35:17.732
when you eating this
because it's only just boiled.

35:17.772 --> 35:21.305
Not fried. Not...
Oh, I don't feel guilty.

35:21.335 --> 35:25.407
Oh, it's fantastic.
Oh, it's superb.

35:25.437 --> 35:28.409
Wonderful.
Thank you.

35:35.614 --> 35:37.546
So, Jose,
what's left of the pig?

35:37.586 --> 35:39.247
A couple of hams
and not much else.

35:39.287 --> 35:41.548
Well, the everything
is on salt right now.

35:41.588 --> 35:44.250
So the shoulders
and the legs are in salt?

35:44.290 --> 35:45.907
They're on salt.
They're gonna be in salt

35:45.921 --> 35:47.422
for about three months,

35:47.452 --> 35:49.423
and then they're going
to be smoked

35:49.453 --> 35:51.355
and they are a prosciutto.

35:51.395 --> 35:54.757
And they are fantastic.

35:54.797 --> 35:57.729
So you spoke about
Fado and sadness,

35:57.759 --> 36:00.661
but, you know,
after a few drinks,

36:00.701 --> 36:02.102
everybody gets very happy,
you know?

36:02.132 --> 36:04.764
Good.

36:04.804 --> 36:06.735
Means, "With wine, happiness."

36:06.765 --> 36:08.106
- Yeah!
- Cheers.

36:08.136 --> 36:10.167
- Yeah.
- Happiness, happiness.

36:10.207 --> 36:12.669
Thank you.

38:13.489 --> 38:15.020
Cheers.

38:18.853 --> 38:22.155
Now it's time
for the francesinha,

38:22.195 --> 38:25.497
which translates
as little French girl?

38:25.528 --> 38:26.828
Yeah, yeah.

38:26.858 --> 38:28.222
But I understand
she's not so little.

38:28.229 --> 38:29.800
- No, it's not.
- No.

38:29.830 --> 38:31.602
It's your first time,
francesinha?

38:31.632 --> 38:33.333
- It is.
- Really?

38:33.363 --> 38:35.634
You have this look
on your face like...

38:35.664 --> 38:37.205
You look worried.

38:37.235 --> 38:40.307
- Good luck.
- It's gonna be okay, right?

38:40.337 --> 38:42.609
Oh, here we go.

38:42.639 --> 38:44.940
- Oh, thank you.
- What do we got?

38:44.970 --> 38:46.942
Good Lord, look at that thing.

38:46.972 --> 38:49.343
Is there a vegetable in there?

38:49.373 --> 38:51.475
- Only meat.
- Oh, my God.

38:51.515 --> 38:53.846
It weighs, like, a ton.

39:02.882 --> 39:05.884
So it's bread, ham...

39:05.924 --> 39:06.885
Mm-hmm.

39:06.925 --> 39:08.826
Steak...

39:08.856 --> 39:10.387
Sausage, and a bit of...

39:10.427 --> 39:12.489
- Linguica.
- Yeah, linguica.

39:15.331 --> 39:18.663
And then the sauce
has many things like beer,

39:18.693 --> 39:22.966
Port wine, spicy, tomato.

39:22.996 --> 39:25.898
- Cheese.
- A lot of cheese. A lot.

39:25.938 --> 39:28.069
Wow.

39:28.099 --> 39:30.241
What a construction.

39:30.271 --> 39:34.844
Meat, cheese, fat and bread?
It's the immortal combination.

39:34.874 --> 39:36.305
Yeah, it's the ultimate solution

39:36.345 --> 39:38.206
for a hangover or too much pork.

39:44.580 --> 39:46.181
That is delicious.

39:46.211 --> 39:48.012
Oh, that's good.
It's really, really good.

39:48.053 --> 39:49.884
Are there a lot
of places making this?

39:49.914 --> 39:51.085
- Mmm.
- A lot.

39:51.115 --> 39:52.656
- Yeah.
- Everyone does.

39:52.686 --> 39:54.917
And this is a Oporto
thing specifically?

39:54.957 --> 39:57.689
- Yes.
- Yeah.

39:57.719 --> 39:59.660
What's the relative rate

39:59.690 --> 40:03.663
per capita of heart-related
disease in this country?

40:03.693 --> 40:05.094
I'm just curious.

40:05.124 --> 40:07.666
It depends on how many
francesinha you had.

40:07.696 --> 40:09.697
Oh, right.

40:40.948 --> 40:44.050
Oh-oh, oh-oh.
How are you doing?

40:46.652 --> 40:50.254
No, I don't know. Today?
You guys need any fish?

40:50.294 --> 40:52.055
Thank you.

41:41.028 --> 41:44.660
Everything old is new again,
maybe not.

41:44.690 --> 41:47.232
I come close sometimes
to believing

41:47.262 --> 41:49.493
that nothing
actually ever changes,

41:49.533 --> 41:51.895
that we are trapped
in our destiny,

41:51.935 --> 41:53.466
hurtling or limping

41:53.496 --> 41:55.968
or being dragged
towards the inevitable.

41:55.998 --> 41:59.000
That saudade refers
not to a long-lost place,

41:59.040 --> 42:00.601
but a long-lost time

42:00.641 --> 42:03.173
when we were all
young and innocent.

42:03.203 --> 42:06.305
Saudade can help
you value things.

42:06.345 --> 42:09.677
Be grateful for just a sunset.
Enjoy that. Smile.

42:09.707 --> 42:11.578
- Enjoy it now.
- Yes.

42:11.608 --> 42:12.779
Because tomorrow we die.

42:12.809 --> 42:13.950
Yeah, you never know.

